eir own successes, and manage the knowledge they''ve acquired - but even so it has been shown that the overwhelming majority of attempts fail.',1,143312),(9186,188,'大量研究证实了这一点，涵盖了广泛的业务环境：分行、零售店、房地产中介、工厂、呼叫中心……仅举几例。',173960,'A host of studies confirm this, covering a wide range of business settings: branch banks, retail stores, real estate agencies, factories, call centres ... to name but a few.（Q32）',1,160001),(9187,188,'那么为什么很少有经理在第二次或第三次把事情做好呢？',180480,'So why do so few managers get things right the second or third time?',1,173961),(9188,188,'让我们考虑一个失败的原因——过于信任那些成功运作的人，我们应该说是“专家”。想要应用现有知识的经理通常会先去找专家——比如设计并经营一家成功的百货公司的人——然后动脑筋。',205130,'Let''s consider one reason for failure - placing too much trust in the people who are running the successful operation, the ''experts'' shall we say. Managers who want to apply existing knowledge typically start off by going to an expert - such as the person who designed and is running a successful department store - and picking their brains.',1,180487),(9189,188,'现在，如果您想粗略了解特定系统或了解较小的孤立问题，则可以使用此方法。',216550,'Now, this approach can be used if you, want to gain a rough understanding of a particular system, or understand smaller, isolated problems.（Q33）',1,205133),(9190,188,'问题是，即使是专家也不能完全掌握整个事情，因为当涉及到复杂的系统时，过程的各个组成部分是相互交织的。',230000,'The trouble is, even the expert doesn''t fully grasp the whole thing because when it comes to complex systems, the individual components of the process are interwoven with one another.',1,216553),(9191,188,'专家永远无法完全访问必要的信息。',235000,'The expert never has complete access to the necessary information.',1,230001),(9192,188,'由于专家通常不知道自己的无知，情况变得更加复杂。',244400,'And the situation''s complicated even further by the fact that experts are usually not aware of their own ignorance.',1,235001),(9193,188,'无知可以有多种形式。',248010,'The ignorance can take various forms.',1,244406),(9194,188,'例如，系统的很多细节对管理者来说是不可见的。',253970,'For instance, a lot of details of the system are invisible to managers.',1,248018),(9195,188,'有些可能难以描述在工作中学到